# Project CLAUDE.md template

# This is a sanitized template based on the CLAUDE.md I keep in the root of
# my Wisent backends repo. The literal credentials and internal infrastructure
# URLs have been replaced with placeholders. The point is to show the *patterns*
# I use, not to ship credentials.
#
# Pick the sections that apply to your project, replace placeholders with your
# own values, and delete the rest.

## Credentials

# Pasting credentials in CLAUDE.md is convenient but DANGEROUS - anything in
# this file is loaded into the model's context every turn. Anyone reviewing your
# session transcripts will see the keys, and the file usually ends up checked
# into the repo. Prefer environment variables, a 1Password CLI shim, or a
# .env file that is gitignored. Only paste values here if you accept that
# they are effectively published.

AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID: <YOUR_AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID>
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY: <YOUR_AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY>

GitHub PAT (for checking Actions): <YOUR_GITHUB_PAT>
PyPI token (for releases): <YOUR_PYPI_TOKEN>
Hugging Face token (for gated models): <YOUR_HF_TOKEN>

## Hard rules

Do not create new test files. You are prohibited from creating new test files
unless actually requested.

You are banned from using the sleep command. NO SLEEP COMMAND. Use `nohup` for
long-running jobs and inspect logs.

You are not permitted to simplify anything. Do not perform any simple tests.
In case of errors, resolve them. Do not use any backup-substitute paths or
mocks. There should be no hardcoded values. No timeouts. There should be
clear conditions for failure. If there is no failure, continue the process.

## Deployment workflow

This repository is deployed automatically on every commit. The deployment
rules live in `<YOUR_DEPLOYMENT_CONFIG_PATH>` (e.g., `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`).
You can inspect everything happening on the instance. Do not fix things
manually for one instance. Change the deployment script or AMI/image so all
instances pick up the fix. Do not say success until you have:

  1. Triggered a new deployment.
  2. Monitored the deployment until it finishes.
  3. Inspected the new instance.
  4. Reported back that the change works on the freshly deployed instance.

## Diagnosing errors

If there are errors, never guess. Do not say "it is likely". Add logs to
determine THE EXACT CAUSE. If a server is failing, go in and check what is
going wrong. You have the tools to inspect ALL of the code AND ALL of the
logs.

## Repository layout (example - replace with your own)

There are two folders here: one is the source for the `<YOUR_PACKAGE_NAME>`
package, the other is the backend that consumes it. The package can be
published to PyPI with `<YOUR_PYPI_TOKEN>`. Use `<YOUR_DEBUG_MODEL>` (e.g.
`meta-llama/Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct`) when debugging the package locally. The
backend serves the package's functionality.

You are working on this repo locally. Anything pushed to git auto-deploys to
the server. Do not run files locally that are meant to run on the server.

For the inference backend the production model is `<YOUR_INFERENCE_MODEL>`
(e.g. a quantized GGUF served via vLLM). See `docker-compose.inference.yml`
for the full server config. Nothing should be gated.

## Infrastructure shape (example - replace with your own)

We run two instance types on `<YOUR_INSTANCE_FAMILY>` instances (e.g.
`g6e.xlarge`):

  - Training instances run training workers (Celery).
  - Inference instances run inference workers (vLLM).

Each instance type has a green and a blue autoscaling group for seamless
GitHub Actions deploys. Each instance has `<YOUR_GPU_GB>` GB of GPU memory.
There are `<N>` inference workers and `<M>` training workers per instance.
Each instance type scales on demand.

The autoscaling groups sit behind a target group routed via `<YOUR_DOMAIN>`
to the right instance. Because instances cycle, hardcoding instance URLs is
a mistake - always go through the load balancer.

## Benchmark fixing rules

When fixing benchmarks, use the ALREADY CREATED LIST OF FAILURES. Fix them
ONE BY ONE manually. ALL of them can be fixed. Do not say a benchmark does
not exist in lm-eval-harness - it might exist under a different name. Check
the lm-eval-harness tasks README. Do not use backup-substitute paths. Do not
guess extractors or evaluators - use the same evaluator the benchmark uses.
Do not default to log-likelihood evaluation. Do not look at any other
benchmark before fully fixing one. Check both extraction and evaluation.
Track how you generate positive and negative responses for contrastive
pairs. Read the dedicated README if something is unclear. Trust remote code
works fine in lm-eval-harness - read through the codebase if it is not
working for you. DO NOT EDIT lm-eval-harness CODE.

## Running individual commands

For running individual `<YOUR_PACKAGE>` commands, use the `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>`
script (e.g. `run_on_aws.sh`). For any job, use this script. If you change
default values (e.g. running on CPU, reducing trial count), explain why. If
the reason is "this is a simple test", STOP - run with proper defaults.

Do not run `tail` commands (currently broken in this environment). For local
runs, use MPS instead of CPU on Apple Silicon.

## Forbidden commands

These commands are absolutely forbidden:

  - `pkill -f "<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>"` - kills long-running jobs.
  - `pkill <YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>`
  - `killall <YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>`
  - `kill <PID>` for any PID related to `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>`.
  - Any command that would terminate `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>` processes.

Multiple `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>` jobs run in parallel intentionally. NEVER kill
them.

## Background job discipline

Do not poll or repeatedly check log files in a loop. Run the background job,
report the log file location, and wait for the user to ask for updates.

When running long background jobs:

  - Start with `nohup`.
  - Tell the user the log file path.
  - STOP and wait for the user to ask for status.
  - Do not check status more than once per user message.

BANNED ANTI-PATTERN: Repeatedly calling `wc -l` + Read in sequence to
"monitor" a job. This wastes tokens and can cause Claude Code to hang.

Each process run through `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>` is going to save logs to S3 (or
your equivalent log sink).

## Never terminate working processes

  - NEVER terminate a cloud instance or process just because it appears slow.
  - If a process is using CPU/GPU and not showing errors, IT IS WORKING.
  - Long-running processes are NORMAL for large models - let them run.
  - If you think something is stuck, ASK THE USER before taking any action.
  - "No output" or "diagnostics spam" does NOT mean stuck.
  - NEVER create manual workarounds or "simpler tests" to bypass slow
    processes.
  - NEVER present results from arbitrary/guessed parameters as meaningful
    optimization results.
  - The only valid reasons to terminate: explicit user request, actual error
    messages, or instance crash.

## No inline scripts

  - NEVER use inline Python scripts via the dash-c form. Forbidden.
  - NEVER write throwaway code in terminal commands.
  - NEVER pass arbitrary parameters to "make it faster" or "for testing".
  - NEVER hardcode limits, layer ranges, or other parameters unless
    explicitly requested.
  - If a CLI command exists, USE IT.
  - If you need to test code, write a proper script file or use the existing
    CLI infrastructure.
  - Inline scripts lead to: arbitrary parameters, untraceable bugs, wasted
    debugging time.

## Cloud instance management

  - NEVER manually launch instances with `aws ec2 run-instances` or the
    equivalent on your provider.
  - NEVER run SSM commands manually to start jobs.
  - ALWAYS use `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>`.
  - NEVER use timeouts on long-running commands. Use `nohup`.
  - If `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>` times out locally, the job may still be running on
    the cloud instance - check the instance before doing anything else.
  - For long-running extraction jobs, run `<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT>` in background:
    `nohup ./<YOUR_RUN_SCRIPT> ... > job.log 2>&1 &`
  - The script handles: instance launch, setup, job execution, output
    collection, and termination.

